article.description:
Nick Collison had 26 points and 12 rebounds
as Kansas (No. 19 ESPN/USA Today, No. 20 AP) regained its winning touch, beating Tulsa (No. 18, No. 17) 89-80 Wednesday night.
article.headline: Jayhawks regain winning touch behind Collison
article.linkText: Collison, Kansas spoil Tulsa's big night
article.story:
TULSA, Okla. (AP) -- Kansas got back to basics to get back to its
winning ways.

	   The Jayhawks (No. 19 ESPN/USA Today, No. 20 AP), who had lost three of their past four games to tumble from the No. 2 spot in the rankings, outmuscled Tulsa (No. 18, No. 17) on the inside and harassed the Golden Hurricane on the
perimeter in an 89-80 victory Wednesday night.

	   Nick Collison had 26 points and 12 rebounds for Kansas (4-3).
Wayne Simien and Keith Langford scored 19 each, and the Jayhawks
forced 22 turnovers to hand Tulsa its first loss.

	   ''They were just more aggressive, hustled, got every loose ball
and just beat us in the second half,'' said Tulsa coach John
Phillips. ''They were just tougher than we were tonight.''

	   The Jayhawks won despite a poor offensive night from Kirk
Hinrich, who was just 2-of-11 from the field and scored four
points. Tulsa (4-1) also shot 52.5 percent, the first Kansas opponent in
29 games to make more than half its shots.

	   Kevin Johnson was outstanding for Tulsa despite foul trouble,
scoring 23 points and grabbing six rebounds. But he didn't have
enough help in the frontcourt -- Kansas had a 41-32 edge on the
backboards.

	   ''We knew coming into the game that that would be key,'' Johnson
said. ''It's really frustrating.''

	   Kansas coach Roy Williams has been frustrated by his team's lack
of patience on offense, but the Jayhawks were better in that area.

	   ''I liked the unselfishness and patience we had in the second
half,'' he said. ''I wanted us to still attack but be patient with
it, and I think we did that.''

	   Johnson scored 13 in the first half, despite playing just 13
minutes due to foul trouble. Tulsa played on even terms throughout
the half despite getting just one point from Swanson, the team's
second-leading scorer with a 16-point average.

	   Hinrich was just 1-for-9 from the floor in the first half, his
only basket coming on a breakaway layup that gave the Jayhawks
their biggest first-half lead, 32-25, with 4:07 left.

	   Kansas made just two shots the rest of the way while Tulsa went
on a 15-4 run to take a 40-36 lead at halftime. The clincher was a
30-footer at the buzzer by Antonio Reed.

	   ''I told our guys we were not going to give in, we're going to
find out how good a basketball team we are and step up and play,''
Williams said.

	   Tulsa led by seven early in the second half after a 3-pointer by
Swanson, and then Langford got going.

	   He scored three baskets in close during a 12-0 run that turned a
45-38 deficit into a 50-45 lead. Johnson sat for a part of that
time after getting his third foul.

	   Langford scored six in a row moments later -- a baseline jumper,
two free throws and a fastbreak dunk -- and Collison scored inside
to give Kansas a 60-52 lead with 10:32 to play.

	   The teams essentially traded baskets for the next few minutes. A
driving shot by Swanson got Tulsa within 69-65 with just under 6
minutes to play, then Kansas sealed it with a 10-1 run that
included four points from Collison.

	   During that spurt, Kansas got three straight offensive rebounds
after milking the shot clock. Finally, Collison got fouled and made
two free throws.

	   ''That was important for us,'' Williams said. ''We told the guys
at one timeout, 'Loose ball, you have to get it, don't expect your
teammate to get it.' ''

	   Phillips was disappointed in the loss but encouraged
nonetheless.

	   ''I think we can say, 'Hey, we're pretty good, but we're not
where we want to be,' so we don't need to quit working,'' he said.
''We've got plenty of season left to play.''
